@jd interesting... so the problem is that there's an override of the retry_if_exception_type class https://github.com/gnocchixyz/gnocchi/blob/master/gnocchi/utils.py#L352-L354. Some backward compatibility is provided since it receives an "attempt" instead of a retry_state, but later when it calls the same method of the parent class using the same "attempt" is when it breaks.

To maintain that behaviour we have to have two backward compatibility lanes. One is to allow any retry callback to work with both `retry_state` and whatever it used to accept before (this is done in `BaseRetrying` class and applies for all callbacks). The problem here is that "old-to-new" call signature transition happens in child-parent relationship and skips the `BaseRetrying` class compatibility shim.

So the solution is to make predefined tenacity classes accept both `retry_state` and whatever they used to accept before. This is only done for wait classes right now and i was secretly hoping it could be dumped as well, but probably I'm out of luck in that regard. Brb, fixing.

