I see. That is tricky, but I think it would be worth trying to resolve. By far the most common getter format in C++ should be `const Bar& Foo::get_bar() const`. It would be nice if the API was optimized for it. Manually adding `py::return_value_policy::reference_internal` for most properties is not fun.

Although not that elegant, adding an additional overload for `def_property` and `def_property_readonly` should resolve any RVP issues:
```c++
// existing function
template <typename... Extra>
class_ &def_property(const char *name, const cpp_function &fget, const cpp_function &fset, const Extra& ...extra) {
    return def_property_static(name, fget, fset, is_method(*this), extra...);
}

// additional overload
template <typename Getter, typename... Extra>
class_ &def_property(const char *name, const Getter &fget, const cpp_function &fset, const Extra& ...extra) {
    return def_property(name, cpp_function(fget), fset, return_value_policy::reference_internal, extra...);
}
```

The first overload is resolved when a `cpp_function` getter is passed and it does not apply any RVP. The second overload is for everything else and it sets `reference_internal` by default. RVP doesn't matter for the setter. I think the resulting binding code would be pretty clean, without the extra `py::cpp_function`. The following would all work:

```c++
// default -- reference_internal
.def_property("bar", &Foo::get_bar, &Foo::set_bar)

// cpp_function -- def_property does not override cpp_function's RVP
.def_property("bar", py::cpp_function(&Foo::get_bar, py::return_value_policy::copy), &Foo::set_bar)

// RVP as direct argument -- only the getter cares about RVPs
.def_property("bar", &Foo::get_bar, &Foo::set_bar, py::return_value_policy::copy)
```

It also seems logical to have RVP as a direct `def_property_*` argument, rather than passing it thought `cpp_function`.

One last thing: Having `reference_internal` by default is potentially unsafe if the getter returns an rvalue instead of a reference: `Bar Foo::get_bar() const`. But I think this could be made automatically safe by overriding the policy for rvalues in `type_caster_base` which already happens  in some cases. Actually, is there any use case for having an RVP other than `move` for rvalues? Making it always `move` would remove any possibility for user error in this regard, unless I'm overlooking something.

@tomplus Thanks for working on this! The examples seem to be outdated (IIUC it's compatible with release-3.0), but we definitely want to give the asyncio library (https://github.com/tomplus/kubernetes_asyncio) a try and see what people think about it. 

Asyncio is introduced in Python 3 and we need to support Python 2.7, so we have to keep the old synchronous library in this package. I'd suggest we having a `kubernetes_asyncio` library along with the existing `kubernetes` library, and letting users to switch import path to try the asyncio library. The two libraries shouldn't have any feature/user-visible difference other than the import path change.

The `kubernetes_asyncio` library depends on changes in `python-base`, but IMO maintaining two copies of `python-base` is not what we want. I have to challenge you to backport the change to `python-base` and make it generic for both libraries and minimize the difference. 

We could have two new branches `python:kubernetes_asyncio` and `python-base:kubernetes_asyncio` (replacing the existing `python-base:master` submodule) checking out from existing masters for experimenting - seeing what changes are needed and releasing `7.0.0a2` version. New changes in master can be cherrypicked into these experimental branches. 

@yliaog @mbohlool @dims @sebgoa what do you think?
